<font color="#FF0000">PROPOSED THREAD(S)</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 30 10:45:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
There is some merit to the psychological premiss that we all get &quot;frozen&quot; in particularily good or bad times in our lives.  Perhaps some supportive evidence lies in the fact that we, in a group love to act like 19-year old boys as we have on this site on many occassions.  That is good (sometimes) and that is counterproductive (sometimes).  Class reunions bring back good and not so good memories, do they not?<br>
We need to act silly and play grab ass as we have above.  Perhaps there is the occassion to use strong language to satisfy ourselves that we have gotten our point across, but not always.  Strong language doesn't just mean &quot;F&quot; words, but can also come across in powerfully embraced opinions.<br>
The Viet Nam War is not a clean, concise, clearly stated problem.  This subject is as diverse and complicated as the millions of people involved in it.  Religion and politics are dangerous topics, cannot be totally excluded, but possibly can be played down.  No contributory causation of any kind can be totally ignored.<br>
The sage advice and wisdom to Tom and Chet indicates to me that we have a good chance to create some sacred ground.  A serious resolve to keep the focus on close personal issues rather than global issues may help.  Dealing with those who get out of hand on &quot;this dedicated Thread&quot; should be in the form of tolerance, forgiveness and gentle reminders rather than stern confrontation.  If one persists in &quot;stirring the pot&quot; the others can simply ignore the stimulation and write around that distraction.  Understanding that there are two sides of us, Affect and Cognition, we should be prepared to accomodate one another when emotional diarreah overwhelms our normal &quot;smarts.&quot;<br>
Perhaps it would be wise to have two threads:  One called the &quot;Living room,&quot; where we talk sensibly and another called the &quot;Dog house,&quot; where we are sent by our brothers when two or more of us get too adamant or lock horns.<br>
It is foolish to assume that we can have a perfect thread, but we can work at it.  The rest of the site is not to be ignored.  There exists many appropriate threads for diverse postings and comment.<br>
How about some more feedback before we do anything?<br><br>
Mustang Two Four<br>

